text.tspan: Consider a solution network (blue). For some of the nodes, we have inferred EC50 values for some phosphorylated proteins, obtained
from dose-response data.
Now, we can assess whether the nodes in this network are overall more
sensitive that those which were in the original network but not selected
by the method.
The assumption here is that sensitive nodes are more related to the
perturbation, and therefore the nodes contained in the network should
have high sensitivity (high -logEC50 average). In addition, nodes with
low sensitivity should be excluded from the solution network.
We would expect such a network: since the measurements no longer codify
any perturbation, the resulting networks would make no sense biologically.
Therefore, the differences in sensitivity between nodes included and
excluded from the network would be minimal.
Now, we compare these results to a random control (green). To build these random controls, we shuffle the measurements' labels while leaving
the network topology intact.
A good performer would maximise the difference in average EC50 between nodes included and excluded of the subnetwork, and this
difference should be greater than those obtained with random models.
Taking the top N measurements with most sensitive response, we
can obtain a contextualised subnetwork.
